execution/agents/library/factual/yang-mills/finite-subgroup-convergence.md:25:All three finite groups exhibit first-order bulk phase transitions (confirmed by hysteresis analysis: hot vs. cold starts converge to different values at the transition):
execution/agents/library/factual/yang-mills/finite-subgroup-convergence.md:34:Above β_c the finite group enters a trivial/frozen phase (⟨P⟩ → 1, near-zero string tension, no confinement). SU(2) has no bulk transition.
execution/agents/library/factual/yang-mills/finite-subgroup-convergence.md:36:**Scaling law:** β_c ~ |G|^α with α ≈ 0.6. So β_c → ∞ as |G| → ∞. This means the bulk phase transition is a **lattice artifact of the finite group** that disappears in the continuum limit. Below β_c, each finite group accurately reproduces SU(2) confinement physics; the confining window expands without bound as |G| increases.
execution/agents/library/factual/yang-mills/finite-subgroup-convergence.md:42:At β = 2.0 (within the confining phase for all groups):
execution/agents/library/factual/yang-mills/finite-subgroup-convergence.md:53:1. **The physical barrier to a finite→continuous limit argument appears technical, not fundamental.** Observable convergence is rapid and monotonic. The physics of confinement (plaquette, Wilson loops, Creutz ratios, string tension) is essentially identical to SU(2) in the confining phase of finite groups.
execution/agents/library/factual/yang-mills/finite-subgroup-convergence.md:55:2. **The β_c → ∞ structure is favorable.** For any fixed physical β, sufficiently large finite groups (|G| beyond a threshold set by β_c ~ |G|^0.6) will have β below their critical coupling and thus in the confining phase. A mass gap result for G_n at β < β_c(G_n) could in principle survive the |G_n| → ∞ limit.
